<font color="#FF0000">REPLY TO COOK AND PTSD</font><br>
<tt>Sat Sep 20  0:24:28 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Cook: while the diagnosis of choice for sex abuse as a child, or physical abuse as a child, also is PTSD, it is quite a different form of the &quot;virus&quot; so to speak.  The &quot;ass&quot;ociation of psychiatrists decided that massive childhood abuse, either sexual or physical, qualified the lucky holder to the diagnosis of PTSD-Childhood Origins.  That is far different that the PTSD most vets sustained.<br><br>
Remember, it is based on an experience that is outside the realm of normal human experience. That is the key. Like seeing your buddys head getting blown off.  In today's world, car crash victims can get PTSD and often say they &quot;saw my life flash in front of my eyes&quot; as they hang unside down in their trashed car smelling gasoline.  <br><br>
Children who get incested, molested, or worse clearly also are outside the normal range of human experience, hence they too get included in the diagnosis.  Treatment,however, is quite different for the two.<br><br>
No one that I know, knows why some healthy individuals end up with PTSD and others don't. It has nothing to do with family values, religion, etc.  Perhaps it is just a moment in someones life when the battle armor (psychological) was gapping open, or dropping? I don't know).<br><br>
I do know that PTSD and its many variations are real, and do respond to a three prong attack, i.e. a triple method of treatment. 1 being medication, 2 being de sensitization, and 3 being insight orientated therapy.  Psychobabble you think, right?  Ask any vet over at the Riverside VA if I am telling the truth or not.  If you know the VA at Riverside, you must know McGoo.  Do you?  Man was in and out of the veteran counseling groups there for 20 years. He figured he could self medicate his demons with whiskey. He didn't want to become an alcoholic, so he only bought pint bottles, one at a time. 12 times a day.  By nightfall his demons were drunk and asleep, and so was he.  Now he has been clean and dry for over 9 years, and he deals with his flashbacks and other PTSD remenants on a day by day basis, as he does with his sobriety.  He is one helluva guy. I consider myself fortunate to be able to be one of many that helped him before he blew out his liver and his life.<br><br>
The point of all of this is that, despite what Chet opinioned, I have seen PTSD at all levels of society, from those with strong families and intack values, to those with shattered families and a history of domestic violence and mayhem.  No one seems to know why, just that when you got it, you got it.  CLearly you don't.<br><br>
Now, as to Pre - Traumatic Macho Syndrome, which you do have, which is the desire to kill commies whereever they are, shoot the wings off of enemy attack craft, and cause general upset to the enemy, I think the only traumatic stress disorder you caused was to Charlie.<br><br>
A warning is in order. Most shrinks don't know their ass from PTSD, and that is multipled by 10 when you are dealing with doc's inside the V.A. System.  Once in awhile you may get an honest one, but don't count on it. If they can't medicate it away, they don't want to see it returning.  This tragedy, the V.A. Hospitals and the treatment of V.N. Vets someday will make 60 minutes and beyond.  It certainly needs to be aired and corrected.  Nuff for now
